versus killing and what happens

00:41:31.022 --> 00:41:35.493 align:middle line:84%
when you go to kill but you end
up accidentally maiming maybe

00:41:35.493 --> 00:41:38.697 align:middle line:84%
because of a lack of
skill or what not.

00:41:38.697 --> 00:41:41.333 align:middle line:84%
>> Yeah, a couple
thoughts come to mind,

00:41:41.333 --> 00:41:45.470 align:middle line:84%
one is that many cultures
and actually including sort

00:41:45.470 --> 00:41:52.143 align:middle line:84%
of European hunter traditions
have stories and rituals

00:41:52.143 --> 00:41:55.046 align:middle line:84%
in which the hunter and
the hunted reverse roles

00:41:55.046 --> 00:41:57.349 align:middle line:84%
and the hunter becomes
the hunted.

00:41:57.349 --> 00:42:01.052 align:middle line:84%
And so I think that that
there's a lot of wisdom in that,

00:42:01.052 --> 00:42:04.556 align:middle line:84%
it's not unlike the scene in
some ways, deeply imbedded

00:42:04.556 --> 00:42:08.026 align:middle line:84%
in a lot of hunting
cultures traditions.

00:42:09.127 --> 00:42:17.002 align:middle line:84%
And for me the fear
of maiming an animal,

00:42:17.002 --> 00:42:19.604 align:middle line:84%
the fear of not having
an instant

00:42:19.604 --> 00:42:24.442 align:middle line:84%
or nearly instant
kill was a deep one

00:42:24.442 --> 00:42:29.848 align:middle line:84%
and I've interviewed a lot
of hunters who particularly

00:42:29.848 --> 00:42:32.584 align:middle line:84%
who came to hunting as adults,
I did some graduate research

00:42:32.584 --> 00:42:37.589 align:middle line:84%
on this, and it's a
very common deep fear.

00:42:37.589 --> 00:42:41.059 align:middle line:84%
That is the last thing that
people want to experience.

00:42:41.059 --> 00:42:43.561 align:middle line:84%
And frankly it's true for a
lot of lifelong hunters too.

00:42:43.561 --> 00:42:45.597 align:middle line:84%
You know, my uncle has
been hunting since he was

00:42:45.597 --> 00:42:52.003 align:middle line:84%
in his teens and he has had the
experience of wounding an animal

00:42:52.003 --> 00:42:54.873 align:middle line:84%
and not finding it, and not
knowing whether it survived

00:42:54.873 --> 00:42:56.307 align:middle line:90%
or not.

00:42:56.307 --> 00:43:00.979 align:middle line:84%
Despite being a very
disciplined, very skilled hunter

00:43:00.979 --> 00:43:06.017 align:middle line:84%
and he has come close in his
mind to not doing it again

00:43:06.017 --> 00:43:11.256 align:middle line:84%
because it such a painful
emotional experience to-- -

00:43:11.256 --> 00:43:13.158 align:middle line:84%
>> I would think you'd
take that home with you.

00:43:13.158 --> 00:43:14.492 align:middle line:90%
>> Very much so.

00:43:14.492 --> 00:43:16.861 align:middle line:84%
And any hunter I've
talked to who has had

00:43:16.861 --> 00:43:24.536 align:middle line:84%
that experience has expressed
a lot of regret and some doubts

00:43:24.536 --> 00:43:27.372 align:middle line:84%
about what they would
do next time.

00:43:27.372 --> 00:43:28.373 align:middle line:90%
>> Right.

00:43:28.373 --> 00:43:29.307 align:middle line:84%
>> And certainly
perhaps about the choice

00:43:29.307 --> 00:43:30.675 align:middle line:90%
that they made in that moment.

00:43:30.675 --> 00:43:36.881 align:middle line:84%
So, for me learning marksmanship
and being disciplined

00:43:36.881 --> 00:43:39.384 align:middle line:84%
about the choices that I
made in terms of the shots

00:43:39.384 --> 00:43:43.455 align:middle line:84%
that I'd be willing to
take was quite important.

00:43:43.455 --> 00:43:48.426 align:middle line:84%
I also had a very humbling
experience when I was

00:43:48.426 --> 00:43:50.895 align:middle line:84%
out there I think in
my second or third--

00:43:50.895 --> 00:43:54.466 align:middle line:84%
my second season
of hunting deer.

00:43:54.466 --> 00:43:57.635 align:middle line:84%
When I took a shot
and completely missed

00:43:57.635 --> 00:44:00.505 align:middle line:84%
as with the bow and
I mostly it's hunting

00:44:00.505 --> 00:44:02.741 align:middle line:84%
with a firearm 'cause for me
I feel much more confident

00:44:02.741 --> 00:44:06.111 align:middle line:84%
to be able to make that
quick instant kill,

00:44:06.111 --> 00:44:08.046 align:middle line:84%
but at that time I
was hunting with a bow

00:44:08.046 --> 00:44:10.949 align:middle line:90%
and I completely missed.

00:44:10.949 --> 00:44:16.287 align:middle line:84%
What came over me was a
deep shame that I have made

00:44:16.287 --> 00:44:18.623 align:middle line:84%
such a bad choice
because that could

00:44:18.623 --> 00:44:20.158 align:middle line:90%
so easily have been a wound,

00:44:20.158 --> 00:44:24.963 align:middle line:84%
if I had that little
control over, over that shot.

00:44:24.963 --> 00:44:28.900 align:middle line:84%
And even though the range
was good and I had practiced

00:44:28.900 --> 00:44:33.171 align:middle line:84%
and all that, it was-- the
conditions were such that I--

00:44:33.171 --> 00:44:35.740 align:middle line:84%
that I made, you
know, quite a missed.

00:44:35.740 --> 00:44:41.479 align:middle line:84%
And that already
enforced my commitment

00:44:41.479 --> 00:44:43.214 align:middle line:90%
to making better choices.

00:44:43.214 --> 00:44:45.617 align:middle line:84%
And then I went-- made
another mistake just like it.

00:44:45.617 --> 00:44:47.218 align:middle line:84%
[laughs] It was, you know,
deeply humbling to realize

00:44:47.218 --> 00:44:49.754 align:middle line:84%
that whatever your
marksmanship skills

00:44:49.754 --> 00:44:53.024 align:middle line:84%
and whatever your
good intentions

00:44:53.024 --> 00:44:57.662 align:middle line:84%
and whatever your ethics, you
can still have bad judgment

00:44:57.662 --> 00:45:00.965 align:middle line:84%
and make a poor choice
in the moment.

00:45:00.965 --> 00:45:03.868 align:middle line:84%
And I think that's
something we all hunters lived

00:45:03.868 --> 00:45:06.438 align:middle line:90%
with as a potential.

00:45:06.438 --> 00:45:08.907 align:middle line:84%
The better they get, the
better their discipline

00:45:08.907 --> 00:45:13.778 align:middle line:84%
and the better their,
you know, their judgment,

00:45:13.778 --> 00:45:17.682 align:middle line:84%
the less likely I think
that is to happen.

00:45:17.682 --> 00:45:18.883 align:middle line:90%
And thankfully for me it has--

00:45:18.883 --> 00:45:22.987 align:middle line:84%
I've never actually
wounded an animal and the--

00:45:22.987 --> 00:45:26.157 align:middle line:84%
but the fear of doing
it remains with me.

00:45:26.157 --> 00:45:30.261 align:middle line:84%
>> What about-- I know that
in your book you stated that,

00:45:30.261 --> 00:45:33.865 align:middle line:84%
"It's not as though
there's a joy in killing."

00:45:33.865 --> 00:45:38.136 align:middle line:84%
But for some of the hunters
there is a joy in killing.

00:45:38.136 --> 00:45:41.773 align:middle line:84%
This is a different
mindset, you know?

00:45:41.773 --> 00:45:42.907 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:45:42.907 --> 00:45:46.177 align:middle line:84%
>> To go out and there's
an actual joy or thrill

00:45:46.177 --> 00:45:49.013 align:middle line:84%
that takes place in
having taken another life.

00:45:49.013 --> 00:45:53.184 align:middle line:84%
And I would think it's a fine
line between being grateful

00:45:53.184 --> 00:45:57.388 align:middle line:84%
that you did it well
and having that thrill

00:45:57.388 --> 00:45:59.157 align:middle line:90%
of taking another life.

00:45:59.157 --> 00:46:00.692 align:middle line:90%
How is that defined to you

00:46:00.692 --> 00:46:03.995 align:middle line:84%
and among the people
that you see as well?

00:46:05.730 --> 00:46:12.437 align:middle line:84%
>> It's a difficult and
tricky terrain to navigate.

00:46:12.437 --> 00:46:17.709 align:middle line:84%
Are there people out there
who genuinely enjoy doing harm

00:46:17.709 --> 00:46:20.545 align:middle line:84%
and inflicting pain
and inflicting death?

00:46:20.545 --> 00:46:25.750 align:middle line:84%
Sure. Some of them are hunters;
some of them are not hunters,

00:46:25.750 --> 00:46:29.821 align:middle line:84%
whether those people are
more common among hunters

00:46:29.821 --> 00:46:32.257 align:middle line:84%
than among the general
population,

00:46:32.257 --> 00:46:35.159 align:middle line:90%
I don't know, I'm not sure.

00:46:36.361 --> 00:46:39.130 align:middle line:90%
Those people exist.

00:46:39.130 --> 00:46:41.933 align:middle line:84%
That mindset, that
sadism essentially exist

00:46:41.933 --> 00:46:44.435 align:middle line:84%
in the world we all know this
whether it's afflicted on humans

00:46:44.435 --> 00:46:46.604 align:middle line:90%
or animals, or whatever.

00:46:48.072 --> 00:46:51.876 align:middle line:84%
But I also think there's a
lot of gray area and a lot

00:46:51.876 --> 00:46:57.649 align:middle line:84%
of misinterpretation
of the joy in the hunt.

00:46:57.649 --> 00:47:02.520 align:middle line:84%
And I have essay coming
out later this year about--

00:47:02.520 --> 00:47:06.591 align:middle line:84%
I call it, "Killing and
Grinning and smiling,

00:47:06.591 --> 00:47:08.059 align:middle line:90%
the ethics of emotion."

00:47:08.059 --> 00:47:11.930 align:middle line:84%
Now, when we see a
picture of a hunter

00:47:11.930 --> 00:47:14.432 align:middle line:90%
with a dead animal who's--

00:47:14.432 --> 00:47:18.436 align:middle line:84%
and the hunter is
smiling into the camera.

00:47:18.436 --> 00:47:23.207 align:middle line:84%
That symbol, that image
evokes very different sorts

00:47:23.207 --> 00:47:28.513 align:middle line:84%
of responses in us depending
on our feelings about hunting

00:47:28.513 --> 00:47:31.282 align:middle line:84%
and our experiences,
and a lot of this,

00:47:31.282 --> 00:47:33.284 align:middle line:90%
what is the smile about?

00:47:33.284 --> 00:47:34.419 align:middle line:90%
What is that?

00:47:34.419 --> 00:47:40.625 align:middle line:84%
Is it pride in having
accomplished something,

00:47:40.625 --> 00:47:45.863 align:middle line:84%
and perhaps a still-- a charge
of energy from the hunt,

00:47:45.863 --> 00:47:49.300 align:middle line:84%
you know, that, you
know, it's intense.

00:47:49.300 --> 00:47:52.870 align:middle line:84%
There's energy in it and that
can come out in the smile.

00:47:52.870 --> 00:47:55.773 align:middle line:84%
And there can be joy in having
done something well especially

00:47:55.773 --> 00:47:57.508 align:middle line:90%
who is difficult.

00:47:57.508 --> 00:48:00.144 align:middle line:84%
That's very different
interpretation

00:48:00.144 --> 00:48:03.681 align:middle line:84%
from the way I used to
interpret those pictures

00:48:03.681 --> 00:48:07.952 align:middle line:84%
which is this is sadism,
this is joy in death,

00:48:07.952 --> 00:48:10.822 align:middle line:84%
this is joy in the act of
killing in that precise act not

00:48:10.822 --> 00:48:13.458 align:middle line:90%
in the whole process of the hunt

00:48:13.458 --> 00:48:16.594 align:middle line:84%
and perhaps some
pride and success.

00:48:16.594 --> 00:48:24.035 align:middle line:84%
So, I find myself needing
to not judge too quickly

00:48:24.035 --> 00:48:25.870 align:middle line:90%
and to really try to understand.

00:48:25.870 --> 00:48:28.539 align:middle line:84%
You know, there are people
I don't want to hunt with,

00:48:28.539 --> 00:48:31.476 align:middle line:84%
there are plenty of people that
I'd be happy to hang out with,

00:48:31.476 --> 00:48:34.645 align:middle line:84%
but I would not hunt with just
through the emotion, attitude,

00:48:34.645 --> 00:48:36.781 align:middle line:84%
ethics, philosophy,
it doesn't match mine

00:48:36.781 --> 00:48:40.218 align:middle line:84%
so I won't hunt with
that person.

00:48:40.218 --> 00:48:43.955 align:middle line:84%
But I also want to remain
open to the possibility

00:48:43.955 --> 00:48:50.762 align:middle line:84%
that their attitude or their
emotion doesn't carry necessary

00:48:50.762 --> 00:48:54.399 align:middle line:84%
the negative moral conditions
that I might suspect.

00:48:54.399 --> 00:48:56.701 align:middle line:84%
So, there's-- it's tricky--
a tricky [inaudible].

00:48:56.701 --> 00:49:00.471 align:middle line:84%
>> It has been and thank you for
explaining your feelings on that

00:49:00.471 --> 00:49:03.875 align:middle line:84%
and how you've gone through
that that transformation

00:49:03.875 --> 00:49:06.911 align:middle line:84%
of viewing it from
way into another.

00:49:06.911 --> 00:49:10.048 align:middle line:84%
And it-- you bring up
another really big point

00:49:10.048 --> 00:49:14.118 align:middle line:84%
and that is we are part
animals, we are competitive

00:49:14.118 --> 00:49:15.820 align:middle line:84%
with each other, you
can get into a lot

00:49:15.820 --> 00:49:19.524 align:middle line:84%
of different philosophical
debates on why that is,

00:49:19.524 --> 00:49:23.761 align:middle line:84%
and yet we separate ourselves
out as being other than the rest

00:49:23.761 --> 00:49:27.298 align:middle line:84%
of the animal kingdom and
that there is natural prey

00:49:27.298 --> 00:49:29.400 align:middle line:90%
and there is a natural affinity

00:49:29.400 --> 00:49:31.936 align:middle line:84%
for hunting among
the animal kingdom,

00:49:31.936 --> 00:49:37.675 align:middle line:84%
why are humans not
considered natural predators?

00:49:37.675 --> 00:49:39.777 align:middle line:84%
>> Yeah, I think
it's good question.

00:49:39.777 --> 00:49:41.846 align:middle line:84%
There's, you know,
archeological evidence

00:49:41.846 --> 00:49:44.415 align:middle line:84%
that we were both hunting
and scavenging as, you know,

00:49:44.415 --> 00:49:47.585 align:middle line:84%
hominids or pre-humans
millions of years ago,

00:49:47.585 --> 00:49:49.420 align:middle line:84%
a million to two
million years ago.

00:49:49.420 --> 00:49:53.257 align:middle line:84%
So and chimpanzees
also hunt monkeys.

00:49:53.257 --> 00:49:55.426 align:middle line:84%
You know, it doesn't-- that's
not the bulk of their diet

00:49:55.426 --> 00:50:01.165 align:middle line:84%
but it's part of the
primate experience, you know?

00:50:01.165 --> 00:50:02.400 align:middle line:90%
>> Right.

00:50:02.400 --> 00:50:05.903 align:middle line:84%
>> And I think the argument
is that though we might

00:50:05.903 --> 00:50:10.007 align:middle line:84%
in some sense be natural
predators we're also very

00:50:10.007 --> 00:50:11.809 align:middle line:90%
cultural predators.

00:50:11.809 --> 00:50:15.279 align:middle line:84%
If we are predators it's
very culturally constructed

00:50:15.279 --> 00:50:18.116 align:middle line:84%
and framed in very
different ways, in, you know,

00:50:18.116 --> 00:50:19.750 align:middle line:84%
in different cultures
around the world.

00:50:19.750 --> 00:50:25.156 align:middle line:84%
So, some cultures values will
say, "We hunt in this way

00:50:25.156 --> 00:50:29.026 align:middle line:84%
but we don't hunt at all or
we hunt in this other ways."

00:50:29.026 --> 00:50:33.998 align:middle line:84%
And so it is certainly not
just nature expressing itself,

00:50:33.998 --> 00:50:37.902 align:middle line:84%
it's perhaps some kind of
nature expressing itself and lot

00:50:37.902 --> 00:50:40.872 align:middle line:84%
of cultural and culture
expressing themselves as well.

00:50:40.872 --> 00:50:46.210 align:middle line:84%
>> On that note let's talk
about the Africans and the kudu.

00:50:46.210 --> 00:50:48.846 align:middle line:84%
Let's talk about that
and I also want to get

00:50:48.846 --> 00:50:53.651 align:middle line:84%
into the Tibetan path for
consuming animal flesh

00:50:53.651 --> 00:50:56.254 align:middle line:84%
which is what quite
convoluted and interesting.

00:50:56.254 --> 00:50:58.523 align:middle line:84%
So, we see how we
each deal with this,

00:50:58.523 --> 00:51:01.292 align:middle line:84%
how different cultures deal with
it, let's talk about the kudu.

00:51:01.292 --> 00:51:06.063 align:middle line:84%
>> Sure. So, in one of David
Attenborough's nature series I

00:51:06.063 --> 00:51:11.435 align:middle line:84%
believe in it's in the series
Mammals, the last section

00:51:11.435 --> 00:51:13.771 align:middle line:84%
of that is about
the human mammal

00:51:13.771 --> 00:51:20.244 align:middle line:90%
and he has a wonderful scene

00:51:20.244 --> 00:51:26.551 align:middle line:84%
where several Kalahari san
Bushmen are hunting a kudu

00:51:26.551 --> 00:51:28.019 align:middle line:90%
and this is this ancient form

00:51:28.019 --> 00:51:29.854 align:middle line:84%
of hunting called
the persistence hunt

00:51:29.854 --> 00:51:34.926 align:middle line:84%
which means they chase it down,
they run for hours tracking

00:51:34.926 --> 00:51:40.765 align:middle line:84%
with incredible skill until the
animal basically falls over.

00:51:40.765 --> 00:51:48.005 align:middle line:84%
And I saw that before I
started hunting, in the end one

00:51:48.005 --> 00:51:53.144 align:middle line:84%
